En dan zou ik een scheduler maken die elk uur een keer triggert en dan kijkt of er al een week voorbij is sinds de laatste reset
    public void resetWeeklyPlaytime() {
        int weekNumber = Calendar.getInstance().get(Calendar.WEEK_OF_YEAR);
        weeklyPlaytime.clear();
    }

 Here is how I would implement a scheduler to reset the weekly playtime map every week:

```java
public class PlaytimeTracker {

  private Map<UUID, Integer> weeklyPlaytime = new HashMap<>();

  private int lastResetWeek = -1;

  public void scheduleWeeklyReset() {
    Bukkit.getScheduler().scheduleSyncRepeatingTask(this, () -> {
      int currentWeek = Calendar.getInstance().get(Calendar.WEEK_OF_YEAR);
      if (currentWeek != lastResetWeek) {
        resetWeeklyPlaytime();
        lastResetWeek = currentWeek; 
      }
    }, 0L, 20L); 
  }

  private void resetWeeklyPlaytime() {
    weeklyPlaytime.clear();
  }

}
```

The key points:

- Store the week number of the last reset 
- Schedule a task to run every second (20 ticks) 
- In the task, check if the current week differs from the stored last reset week
- If so, reset the playtime map and update the last reset week

This will reset the playtime map every week when the week rolls over. The frequent checking allows it to reset in near real-time at the week transition rather than waiting a full week.

    public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
        return weeklyPlaytime.get(player.getUniqueId());
    }

Kan je me hiermee helpen.
java.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke "java.lang.Integer.intValue()" because the return value of "java.util.Map.get(Object)" is null

Kan je me hiermee helpen. java.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke &quot;java.lang.Integer.intValue()&quot; because the return value of &quot;java.util.Map.get(Object)&quot; is null
    public void resetWeeklyPlaytime() {
        scheduleWeeklyReset();
    }

 This NullPointerException is happening because the weeklyPlaytime map does not contain a value for the player's UUID when you call weeklyPlaytime.get(player.getUniqueId()). 

There are a couple ways to fix this:

1. Check for null before calling get():

```java 
public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
  Integer playtime = weeklyPlaytime.get(player.getUniqueId());
  if (playtime == null) {
    return 0; 
  }
  return playtime;
}
```

2. Use Map.getOrDefault() to return a default value if null:

```java
public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
  return weeklyPlaytime.getOrDefault(player.getUniqueId(), 0); 
}
```

3. Initialize the map value to 0 when a player first joins:

```java
public void playerJoined(Player player) {
  weeklyPlaytime.putIfAbsent(player.getUniqueId(), 0);
  // other logic
}
```

The core issue is that get() returns null if the key is not present in the map. So you need to account for that case to avoid the NullPointerException.

public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
    return weeklyPlaytime.get(player.getUniqueId());
}

 To avoid the NullPointerException when getting the weekly playtime for a player, you can use the Map.getOrDefault() method:

```java
public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
  return weeklyPlaytime.getOrDefault(player.getUniqueId(), 0);
}
```

This will return 0 if the player's UUID is not present in the weeklyPlaytime map, rather than throwing an exception.

Some other options:

- Check for null before getting:

```java
Integer playtime = weeklyPlaytime.get(player.getUniqueId());
if(playtime == null) {
  return 0; 
}
return playtime;
```

- Initialize the value to 0 on first join:

```java 
public void playerJoined(Player player) {
  weeklyPlaytime.putIfAbsent(player.getUniqueId(), 0);
  // other logic
}
```

The key point is that you need to handle the case where get() returns null, either by providing a default value or checking for null explicitly. getOrDefault() provides a concise way to handle this.

package nl.officialfox.staffmanage;

import org.bukkit.Bukkit;
import org.bukkit.entity.Player;

import java.time.Duration;
import java.time.Instant;
import java.util.Calendar;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.UUID;

public class PlaytimeTracker {
    private Map&lt;Player, Instant&gt; joinTimes = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    private Map&lt;UUID, Integer&gt; weeklyPlaytime = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();

    public void playerJoined(Player player) {
        joinTimes.put(player, Instant.now());
    }

    public String getPlaytime(Player player) {
        Instant joinTime = joinTimes.get(player);
        if (joinTime == null) return &quot;0m&quot;;

        Duration playtime = Duration.between(joinTime, Instant.now());

        long minutes = playtime.toMinutes();
        return String.format(&quot;%dm&quot;, minutes);
    }

    public void playerLeft(Player player) {
        joinTimes.remove(player);
    }

    public String getRank(Player player) {

        if (player.hasPermission(&quot;staff.helper&quot;)) {
            return &quot;staff.helper&quot;;
        }

        if (player.hasPermission(&quot;staff.mod&quot;)) {
            return &quot;staff.mod&quot;;
        }

        if (player.hasPermission(&quot;staff.admin&quot;)) {
            return &quot;staff.admin&quot;;
        }

        return &quot;&quot;;

    }

    public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
        return weeklyPlaytime.get(player.getUniqueId());
    }

    //java.lang.NullPointerException: Cannot invoke &quot;java.lang.Integer.intValue()&quot; because the return value of &quot;java.util.Map.get(Object)&quot; is null
    public void resetWeeklyPlaytime() {
        scheduleWeeklyReset();
    }

    private int lastResetWeek = -1;

    public void scheduleWeeklyReset() {
        Bukkit.getScheduler().scheduleSyncRepeatingTask(Bukkit.getServer().getPluginManager().getPlugin(&quot;staffmanage&quot;), () -&gt; {
            int currentWeek = Calendar.getInstance().get(Calendar.WEEK_OF_YEAR);
            if (currentWeek != lastResetWeek) {
                weeklyPlaytime.clear();
                lastResetWeek = currentWeek;
            }
        }, 0L, 20L);
    }

}

 Here are a few ways to avoid the NullPointerException in the getWeeklyPlaytime() method:

1. Check for null before getting the value:

```java
public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
  Integer weekly = weeklyPlaytime.get(player.getUniqueId());
  if(weekly == null) {
    return 0; 
  }
  return weekly;
}
```

2. Use Map.getOrDefault() to return a default value if null:

```java 
public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
  return weeklyPlaytime.getOrDefault(player.getUniqueId(), 0);
}
```

3. Initialize the map value to 0 on player join:

```java
public void playerJoined(Player player) {
  weeklyPlaytime.putIfAbsent(player.getUniqueId(), 0);
  // other logic
}
```

4. Catch and handle the NullPointerException:

```java
public int getWeeklyPlaytime(Player player) {
  try {
    return weeklyPlaytime.get(player.getUniqueId()); 
  } catch (NullPointerException e) {
    return 0;
  }
}
```

The key is to account for weeklyPlaytime not containing a value for that player's UUID. getOrDefault() provides a clean way to handle this.

 Here is one way you could improve the resetWeeklyPlaytime() method:

```java
public void resetWeeklyPlaytime() {

  // Get current week number
  int currentWeek = Calendar.getInstance().get(Calendar.WEEK_OF_YEAR);

  // Loop through all players
  for (UUID playerUUID : weeklyPlaytime.keySet()) {

    // Check if player has played this week
    if (playerLastPlayedWeek.get(playerUUID) != currentWeek) {  

      // Reset playtime if not played this week
      weeklyPlaytime.put(playerUUID, 0);

    }

  }

  // Update last reset week
  lastResetWeek = currentWeek;

}
```

The key improvements:

- Store each player's last played week in a separate map
- On reset, check each player's last played week against the current week
- Only reset playtime for players that have not played in the current week

This avoids resetting the playtime for all players every week, and instead does it selectively per player based on their last login.

Other enhancements could include:

- Storing the playtime in a database instead of memory
- Adding logging or metrics around playtime resets
- Scheduling the reset on a separate thread to avoid lag

Let me know if you would like me to explain any part of this approach in more detail!

 You're right, my previous code sample referenced a `playerLastPlayedWeek` map that wasn't defined. 

Here is an updated version that declares and populates that map:

```java
public class PlaytimeTracker {

  private Map<UUID, Integer> weeklyPlaytime = new HashMap<>();

  // Map to store last played week for each player
  private Map<UUID, Integer> playerLastPlayedWeek = new HashMap<>();

  public void playerJoined(Player player) {
    // Set initial last played week on first join
    playerLastPlayedWeek.put(player.getUniqueId(), Calendar.getInstance().get(Calendar.WEEK_OF_YEAR));

    // Other logic
  }

  public void resetWeeklyPlaytime() {

    // Get current week
    int currentWeek = Calendar.getInstance().get(Calendar.WEEK_OF_YEAR);

    for (UUID playerUUID : weeklyPlaytime.keySet()) {

      // Check last played week
      if (playerLastPlayedWeek.get(playerUUID) != currentWeek) {

        // Reset playtime
        weeklyPlaytime.put(playerUUID, 0);

      }

    }

    // Update last reset week
    lastResetWeek = currentWeek;

  }

}
```

The key points:

- Declare a `playerLastPlayedWeek` map 
- Populate it with the current week on player
